# Deploy `send-leak-alert` (this repo)

The Expo app calls **`send-leak-alert`** only (`water-leak-monitor/src/lib/iot.ts`). A function named **`super-processor`** or anything else will not receive those requests — use the exact slug **`send-leak-alert`**.

## One-time setup (Windows, PowerShell)

1. Install [Supabase CLI](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/cli/getting-started) if needed.
2. Open a terminal at the **repo root** (the folder that contains `supabase/functions`, e.g. `d:\IOT System`).
3. Log in and link the project (project ref is in the Supabase URL: `https://<project-ref>.supabase.co`):

```powershell
supabase login
supabase link --project-ref YOUR_PROJECT_REF
```

4. Set secrets (Dashboard → Edge Functions → **Secrets**, or CLI):

```powershell
supabase secrets set RESEND_API_KEY=re_xxxxxxxx
# optional:
supabase secrets set RESEND_FROM="Water Leak Monitor <onboarding@resend.dev>"
```

## Deploy the function

From the same repo root:

```powershell
supabase functions deploy send-leak-alert
```

Source lives in `supabase/functions/send-leak-alert/index.ts`.

## Verify

- Dashboard → **Edge Functions** → you must see **`send-leak-alert`** (not only `super-processor`).
- Open **Logs** on **`send-leak-alert`** when testing leaks from the app.
- App Settings must have **Leak alert email** saved; Resend may only deliver to allowed recipients for your sender domain.

## If deploy fails

- Run `supabase link` again if the project changed.
- Ensure the CLI runs from the directory that contains `supabase/functions/send-leak-alert`.
